            <fr:title text="the role of interchange in diagrammatic reasoning">the role of interchange in <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00B8.xml" title="string diagrams" addr="jms-00B8" type="local">diagrammatic reasoning</fr:link></fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>In a 2-category, interchange is strict; in particular, this means that vertical composition and horizontal composition commute strictly with each other. This is very useful for <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00B8.xml" title="string diagrams" addr="jms-00B8" type="local">string diagrams</fr:link>, but it is not strictly necessary. In a <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00B8.xml" title="string diagrams" addr="jms-00B8" type="local">string diagram</fr:link>, strict interchange means that 2-cells can be freely moved upward and downward; so if you want to use diagrammatic reasoning to study something in a structure that has only weak interchange, you need two things:</html:p>
            <html:ol><html:li>The vertical position of a 2-cell is fixed.</html:li>
  <html:li>No two 2-cells should appear at the same vertical position.</html:li></html:ol>
            <html:p>To move a 2-cell up or down is to insert an interchange cell. It is this principle that makes <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00BG.xml" title="homotopy.io" addr="jms-00BG" type="local"><html:code>homotopy.io</html:code></fr:link> work.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
